Furthermore, my results advocate using caution when employing performance indicators in equations relating earnings (or other labour market outcomes) to gender. Higher standards raise quality at the expense of quantity. Performance indicators that weight the latter's fall more heavily than the former's rise will appear artificially low. If used to interpret gender wage gaps, they will undervalue women's work and confound estimates of labour market discrimination. A similar argument was recently made in a study of racial preferences in Major League Baseball.
\f1 \cf2 [#Parsons2011;]
