This paper makes two final contributions. First, it adds to extensive (ongoing) research into peer review. Although mine, to the best of my knowledge, is the first to suggest and document evidence of gender bias in the peer review process (as opposed to its outcome), it joins contemporary or parallel research studying patterns in the editorial process
